60. The papyrus plant was grown principally in Egypt. It grows in water two or three feet deep, and the plant reaches a height ol five or six ieet. The methodos manu- facturing writing material from it is described by Pliny.⁸ The stem of the plant was cut into thin strips, and these strips were laid parallel to one another upon a smooth sur- tace3 another set oi strips was laid upon these at right angles, and the two layers were glued together by the gum which exuded irom the strips when they were moistened . with water. The layers were then hammered together into a single sheet, called a plagula, which was exposed to the sun to dry. The sheets were lrom 5 to ro inches long, and probably one sufficed for an ordinary letter. It more space was needed, several sheets were pasted together.
